Ford Go Bike Trip Data Exploration¶

by Robert Kimani Chege¶

Introduction¶

This data set includes information about approximately 183,000 individual bike rides made in a bike-sharing system covering the greater San Francisco Bay area.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The dataset set is organised into properies of individual bike trips(174952 in total) such as start time and end time, where the trips are made(location of start points and end points) and details of the persons taking the trips such as gender and birth year.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

My main feature of interest is the duration of the bike trips.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

The duration of each trip in relation to the gender, age, bike sharing, and types of user will help support my investigation.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

My variable of interest was the distribution of trip duration. I set x limits to cover 0-3000 seconds in order to get a clear view of the distribution that was initially conventrated on a small area. I also applied log scale to the histogram to get a more widespread distribution. Majority of users take approximately 500 seconds to make a trip.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

The ages above 95 years were invalid, since we don't expect such users to be involved in bike riding I removed this data.

In [180]:
# age duration correlation
sb.regplot(data = bikedf, x = 'age', y = 'duration_sec', truncate=False, x_jitter=0.3, scatter_kws={'alpha':5/10});
plt.title('Correlation Between Member Age and Trip Duration ', size = 15)
plt.xlabel('Age')
plt.ylabel('Duration (seconds)');

Member age and trip duration as seen above have a negative correlation such that the older the member is the less time they will take in their trips. It is also evident that majority of the members no matter the age preferred taking short trips.

Functions to utilize in this section¶

In [192]:
# scatter plot function
def plot_correlation(data, x, y, title, xlabel, ylabel, x_jitter = 0, hue = None, aspect = 0, hue_order = None, fit_reg = False):
    g =sb.FacetGrid(data = data, hue = hue,
                hue_order = hue_order, aspect = aspect)
    g = g.map(sb.regplot, x, y, x_jitter = x_jitter, fit_reg = fit_reg)
    g.add_legend()
    plt.title(title, size = 15)
    plt.xlabel(xlabel)
    plt.ylabel(ylabel)
In [193]:
# poitplot function
def point_plot(data, x, y, ylabel, title, hue, palette, linestyles, dodge):
    sb.pointplot(data = data, x=x, y=y, hue=hue, palette = palette, dodge =dodge, linestyles = linestyles)
    plt.ylabel(ylabel)
    plt.title(title, size = 15)

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

  • There were similar trends of correlation between member age and trip duration for both user types and bike shares, that is a negative correlation. However, it appears that majority of those who did not share their bikes had the longest trip durations.
  • Looking at gender trip durations it's evident that the other gender spends mote time in their trips followed by female then male genders.
  • Customers on average take more time in their trips across all genders.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

  • Among the male and female genders, there's an almost equal level in trip duration for both bike share levels while for the other gender those who do not share bikes take significantly more time in their trips.

Conclusions¶

  • Trips taking long durations are less frequent with the most frequent trips being averagely 500 seconds.
  • Majority of the members are between 20 to 45 years of age with the peak being around mid 30's.
  • Common start stations are also the common end stations.
  • Subscribers are generally more than customers, subscribers being approximately 90% while customers are only 10%.
  • The male gender is the most represented followed by female then the other genders.
  • Majority of the members do not share bikes that is, around 90%.
  • Female members spend more time in their trips than men.
  • 'No' bike share category members are seen to spend averagely more time in their trips.
  • 'Yes' bike share category members are only subscribers and a majority of them are likely to be between the ages 20 and 30.
  • None of the customers is involved in bike sharing.
  • Among customers and subscribers the order of gender counts remains to be male, female then other.
  • The other gender is seen to spend more time in the trips, followed by female then male genders. This trend cuts across bike shares and user types.
  • Across all genders customers are seen to take the longest trip durations.
  • Among the male and female genders, there's an almost equal level in trip duration for both bike share levels while for the other gender those who do not share bikes take significantly more time in their trips.
